data.content:
## C# 14 Implicit Span Conversions Break Expression Trees

**What changed:** C# 14 adds implicit conversions from `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. This changes overload resolution: `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

**Why it breaks:** Expression trees cannot represent ref struct types (`ReadOnlySpan<T>`, `Span<T>`), so the resolved method is incompatible with the `Expression<>` tree.

**Fix — disambiguate the call:**

```csharp
// Option A: call Enumerable.Contains as a static method
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);

// Option B: cast the array so the old overload wins
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);
```

Both force the compiler back to the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which expression trees can represent. The same pattern applies to other `MemoryExtensions` methods (e.g., `SequenceEqual`, `IndexOf`) that now win overload resolution on arrays/spans.
